This river at length discharged itself into Jordan, above the bridge or passage that led into Perea. When, therefore, the Midianites lay on the northern bank of this river, and so were not capable of attaining the passage over Jordan, till they had made through these waters first, it was the Ephraimites’ care and business to maintain the opposite bank, and that indeed all the whole space from the place where the fight began, to Beth—harah and Jordan, that the enemy might be blocked up from all possibility of escape or retiring.
